Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. From January 2020 to May 2021 the Claimant Count in Trafford has increased a 110%. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 4.9% in May 2021 representing an increment of 2.6% from January 2020.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford

The Trafford ward with the largest share of claims in May 2021 was Clifford with 11.6% of all claimants within Trafford. Most of the wards have less claims in May 2021 compared to May 2020 when the claims peak during the first months of the Covid-19 pandemic. Broadheath has the largest reduction in number of claims with -65 followed by Sale Moor (-60), Altrincham (-55), Ashton upon Mersey (-55) and Timperley (-50).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's wards

The wards with higher claimant rate in May 2021 were Clifford with 9.7% and Bucklow-St Martins with 9.6%. The wards where the claimant rate has decreased more from May 2020 to May 2021 are Sale Moor and Ashton upon Mersey with a decrease in rate of -0.9% and -0.9% respectively along with Broadheath with -0.8%.

In Trafford from May 2020 to May 2021 almost all age bands have reduced their claimant count. When considering the reduction of claims the age band 25-29 years had the largest reduction with -130 less claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims, however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic which started in March 2020 this figure increased more sharply compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of Traffords population within each age band shows a higher increase in the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34 compared to the others.

Almost half of Traffords claimants are residents of five of the 21 wards. Almost half of the claimants are under 34 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's wards by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 96.9% from January 2020 to May 2021. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 12.1%. Therefore the number of Universal Credit claimants has doubled in that period.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in May 2021 was Old Trafford with 11.2% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. The MSOA with the highest percentage change from May 2020 to May 2021 is Firswood with 19% change. However, the MSOA with more additional claims in this period is Old Trafford with 282, followed by Firswood (164), Partington (140), Broadheath & Firsway (128) and Gorse Hill (123).

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in May 2021 were Partington with 26.6% and Old Trafford with 25.3%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has grown more from May 2020 to May 2021 were also Old Trafford and Partington with 3.6% and 2.7% respectively along with Firswood with 2.9%.

In Trafford from May 2020 to May 2021 the Over 65 age bands have the largest increment with 77% in the number of Universal Credit claims. When considering the number of additional claims the 5-year age band 20-24 years had the highest with 274 more claims.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age band for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020 the number of claims for all ages rose dramatically from pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. All age bands claims are still slowly rising. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from Mar 2020, while the 16-24 age band has moved from having the third highest rate to having the second highest claims rate.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain elegibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the Searching for Work category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under No work requirements.
